frameDefinitions: A Cause (or associated Actor) causes an ongoing Process to temporarily stop.
An Agent ceases an Activity without completing it. '' 'After the lawsuit, the company stopped producing the once very profitable toy.'
A Process stops at a certain Time and Place.
An Agent pauses in the course of an Activity. '' 'The government froze settlement construction in 1992 to facilitate peace talks.'
This frame concerns Parts of objects that are defined relative to the center or edge of the object.
frameExamples: After the lawsuit, the company <t>stopped</t> producing the once very profitable toy.
The government <t>froze</t> settlement construction in 1992 to facilitate peace talks.
She discarded the <t><fex name='Part'>exterior</fex></t> of the walnut.
listRoleDefinitions: A force, process, or event that produces the interruption.
The <fen>Process</fen> goes into a paused state due to the <fen>Cause</fen> or <fen>Actor</fen>.
An entity which participates in a <fen>Cause</fen>, perhaps volitionally and perhaps not, but effectively causing the interruption.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the interruption occurs.
This role identifies <fen>Agent</fen> that stops the <fen>Activity</fen>.
This role identifies the <fen>Activity</fen> that the <fen>Agent</fen> stops.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the <fen>Agent</fen> stops the <fen>Activity</fen>.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the <fen>Agent</fen> stops the <fen>Activity</fen>.
This role identifies the <fen>Activity</fen> for which an <fen>Agent</fen> is pausing.
An <fen>Agent</fen> pauses in the course of an <fen>Activity</fen>.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> at which an <fen>Agent</fen> pauses in the course of an <fen>Activity</fen>.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where an <fen>Agent</fen> pauses in the course of an <fen>Activity</fen>.
This element describes the <fen>Part</fen> of the larger <fen>Whole</fen>.
An undivided entity having all its <fen>Part</fen>s.
listRoleExamples: <fex>Leaving the page after you've clicked 'Download'</fex> will interrupt the transfer.
Leaving the page after you've clicked 'Download' will interrupt <fex>the transfer</fex>.
In such cases <fex>the server</fex> will automatically interrupt the process.
She only ate the <fex><t>skin</t></fex> of the apple.
She eats only the thick <fex>skin</fex> <fex>of the banana</fex>.
